{"tid":347158,"cid":5,"subCid":0,"title":"美國科學家成功以CRISPR技術修正人類胚胎基因","createTime":"2017-08-04T14:35:57.000Z","updateTime":"2017-08-05T11:25:30.000Z","uid":120678,"like":13,"dislike":1,"uniUserReply":0,"replies":[{"pid":"03b06c2576f40dad8ec3ae62e3be738c1b37560e","tid":347158,"uid":120678,"like":0,"dislike":0,"score":0,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2017-08-04T14:35:57.000Z","msg":"<a href=\"https://www.technologyreview.com/s/608350/first-human-embryos-edited-in-us/\" data-sr-url=\"https://r.lihkg.com/link?u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.technologyreview.com%2Fs%2F608350%2Ffirst-human-embryos-edited-in-us%2F&d=YH7RNHwbniSxePq9ahxhmTM0pwszV1jUpWwTgNsMWwc%3D&h=e33d9c2d\" target=\"_blank\">https://www.technologyreview.com/s/608350/first-human-embryos-edited-in-us/</a><br />\n<br />\nFirst Human Embryos Edited in U.S.<br />\n<br />\nResearchers have demonstrated they can efficiently improve the DNA of human embryos.<br />\n<br />\nby Steve Connor  July 26, 2017<br />\n<br />\nThe first known attempt at creating genetically modified human embryos in the United States has been carried out by a team of researchers in Portland, Oregon, MIT Technology Review has learned.<br />\n<br />\nThe effort, led by Shoukhrat Mitalipov of Oregon Health and Science University, involved changing the DNA of a large number of one-cell embryos with the gene-editing technique CRISPR, according to people familiar with the scientific results.<br />\n<br />\nUntil now, American scientists have watched with a combination of awe, envy, and some alarm as scientists elsewhere were first to explore the controversial practice. To date, three previous reports of editing human embryos were all published by scientists in China.<br />\n<br />\nNow Mitalipov is believed to have broken new ground both in the number of embryos experimented upon and by demonstrating that it is possible to safely and efficiently correct defective genes that cause inherited diseases.<br />\n<br />\nAlthough none of the embryos were allowed to develop for more than a few days&mdash;and there was never any intention of implanting them into a womb&mdash;the experiments are a milestone on what may prove to be an inevitable journey toward the birth of the first genetically modified humans.<br />\n<br />\nEngineering the Perfect Baby<br />\nScientists are developing ways to edit the DNA of tomorrow&rsquo;s children. Should they stop before it&rsquo;s too late?<br />\nIn altering the DNA code of human embryos, the objective of scientists is to show that they can eradicate or correct genes that cause inherited disease, like the blood condition beta-thalassemia. The process is termed &ldquo;germline engineering&rdquo; because any genetically modified child would then pass the changes on to subsequent generations via their own germ cells&mdash;the egg and sperm.<br />\n<br />\nSome critics say germline experiments could open the floodgates to a brave new world of &ldquo;designer babies&rdquo; engineered with genetic enhancements&mdash;a prospect bitterly opposed by a range of religious organizations, civil society groups, and biotech companies.<br />\n<br />\nThe U.S. intelligence community last year called CRISPR a potential &quot;weapon of mass destruction.&rdquo;<br />\n<br />\nShoukhrat Mitalipov is the first U.S.-based scientist known to have edited the DNA of human embryos.<br />\n<br />\nReached by Skype, Mitalipov declined to comment on the results, which he said are pending publication. But other scientists confirmed the editing of embryos using CRISPR. &ldquo;So far as I know this will be the first study reported in the U.S.,&rdquo; says Jun Wu, a collaborator at the Salk Institute, in La Jolla, California, who played a role in the project.<br />\n<br />\nBetter technique<br />\n<br />\nThe earlier Chinese publications, although limited in scope, found CRISPR caused editing errors and that the desired DNA changes were taken up not by all the cells of an embryo, only some. That effect, called mosaicism, lent weight to arguments that germline editing would be an unsafe way to create a person.<br />\n<br />\nBut Mitalipov and his colleagues are said to have convincingly shown that it is possible to avoid both mosaicism and &ldquo;off-target&rdquo; effects, as the CRISPR errors are known. <br />\n<br />\nA person familiar with the research says &ldquo;many tens&rdquo; of human IVF embryos were created for the experiment using the donated sperm of men carrying inherited disease mutations. Embryos at this stage are tiny clumps of cells invisible to the naked eye. MIT Technology Review could not determine which disease genes had been chosen for editing."},{"pid":"c36983d7bce619384694715a05d9c81b70d3a765","tid":347158,"uid":131617,"like":1,"dislike":0,"score":1,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2017-08-04T14:47:07.000Z","msg":"Coordinators <img src=\"/assets/faces/normal/agree.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" />"},{"pid":"80e599d7cf4801245c26597e0a916d4022a3bcfc","tid":347158,"uid":49392,"like":0,"dislike":0,"score":0,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2017-08-04T14:47:14.000Z","msg":"唔係真係人胚胎"},{"pid":"8f8539a7cd5b57c78984cde89cda0384d2a3a892","tid":347158,"uid":65328,"like":1,"dislike":0,"score":1,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2017-08-04T14:53:57.000Z","msg":"<blockquote>Coordinators <img src=\"/assets/faces/normal/agree.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" /></blockquote><br />\n為了蔚藍而潔淨的世界"},{"pid":"324f2b1243cb653b1c944f58d1dda40e0198f579","tid":347158,"uid":24160,"like":0,"dislike":1,"score":-1,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2017-08-04T14:54:24.000Z","msg":"但人工修改..會唔會日後會有其他後遺症都未知?"},{"pid":"170e86863af3e38ca82eb71d349ba4ea90624708","tid":347158,"uid":10890,"like":2,"dislike":0,"score":2,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2017-08-04T14:59:40.000Z","msg":"<blockquote>但人工修改..會唔會日後會有其他後遺症都未知?</blockquote><br />\nCRISPR係直接改某一段dna<br />\n現階段係最直接最少副作用<br />\n同埋今次呢個係將mutate咗 有病嘅dna改返做正常"},{"pid":"0b1acce73e3184aa0f16a3fc35f66f603c453433","tid":347158,"uid":103913,"like":0,"dislike":0,"score":0,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2017-08-04T15:16:00.000Z